    <Folder>
      <name>Intelligence Summary</name>
      <Placemark>
        <name>AI Council Assessment</name>
        <styleUrl>#intel</styleUrl>
        <description>The synthesized intelligence assessment reveals a globally dispersed U.S. military posture with heightened operational tempo across multiple theaters. Strategic airlift and tanker aircraft dominate the tracked missions, with C17, C560, and KC-135/KC-10 platforms operating at high altitudes and speeds, indicating sustained logistics and rapid deployment capabilities. European Command (EUCOM) and NATO operations show particular intensity, with ISR and maritime patrol missions (P8, BE20) concentrated in the North Sea and European littoral. The Indo-Pacific theater demonstrates robust U.S. Navy and Air Force activity, including maritime patrol (P8 over Australia) and amphibious readiness (USS Rushmore transiting Strait of Malacca). The USS George H.W. Bush (CVN-77) is actively transiting the Atlantic en route to Central Command, while USS Gerald R. Ford (CVN-78) and USS Tripoli (LHA-7) remain in-port, suggesting either operational security or deployment delays. Unusual patterns include the high concentration of strategic airlift supporting potential contingencies, and the absence of positional data for key assets (CVN-78, LHA-7) may reflect deliberate operational security. The data suggests a U.S. military posture prioritizing deterrence and rapid response, with particular emphasis on the Middle East, European, and Indo-Pacific regions. The mix of training, utility, and ISR missions indicates a balanced approach to maintaining readiness across all operational domains.</description>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>0,0,0</coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
    </Folder>
